Core idea

👉 if / else is decision-making
👉 OOP is code organization

They don’t compete; they work together.

Where does if / else fit into OOP?

Inside objects, to decide how they behave.

In OOP:

the class defines the behavior

the method performs actions

if/else decides what to do in each situation

Mental example (no code)

Object: Traffic light

State: green, yellow, red

Action: allow_passing()

Inside the object:

if it’s green → allow

else if it’s yellow → caution

else → block

👉 The if/else is inside the object’s method.

Another example: HTTP producer (connecting everything)

Object: DataProducer

It has a method:

produce_response()

Inside that method:

if the data is correct → respond with success

else → respond with error

👉 The decision (if/else) belongs to the object, not scattered across the whole program.

Important difference

❌ Programming without OOP

many loose if/else statements

logic spread everywhere

hard to maintain

✅ With OOP

if/else stays inside the right objects

each object decides for itself

cleaner and more predictable code

Quick analogy

Think of it this way:

if/else = the brain making decisions

OOP = the body organized into organs

The brain decides, but each organ knows what to do.

3-line summary

if/else decides which path to take

OOP defines who decides

In OOP, decisions live inside object methods